rd Investment, Toshiba Corp. Chairman Atsutoshi Nishida told Prime Minister Naoto Kan early participation in the TPP was of vital importance. Within Japanese industries, South Korea is often referred to as the "imaginary enemy." That country is well in front of Japan in terms of FTA strategy. Seoul promotes FTAs as "the key to prosperity." In October, South Korea and the European Union concluded an FTA. That deal is expected to see the EU cut tariffs on nearly all imports from South Korea to zero by 2016. South Korea has also concluded an FTA with the United States, although it is still awaiting ratification by both countries. Full-fledged negotiations between China and South Korea toward conclusion of an FTA are expected to start in the first half of next year. Japan, in marked contrast, does not even have FTA negotiations scheduled with the United States or the EU. In France, the average price of a Panasonic liquid-crystal display TV of 40 to 42 inches is 1,105 euros (about 125,000 yen), according to the Economy, Trade and Industry Ministry. However, a comparable product from South Korea's Samsung Electronics costs 1,003 euros--a difference of more than 100 euros (about 11,000 yen). Without EU tariffs, the imported Samsung product will cost 863 euros (about 97,800 yen)--a price with which Japanese products will obviously be unable to compete. The automobile industry is also expected to suffer if Japan does not become an early participant in the TPP. Combined, the automobile markets in countries and territories with which South Korea has concluded or is negotiating FTAs or EPAs total 40.6 million units. Meanwhile, the combined size of the markets in India, Mexico and the handful of other countries with which Japan has concluded FTAs or EPAs comes to just 8 million units. This disadvantage of more than 30 million units will not be reduced unless Japan looks seriously into market liberalization. A scenario in which Japan does not join the TPP and fails to conclude EPAs with the EU and China, and South Korea's FTAs with the United States, EU and China take effect, would be economically disastrous for Japan, according to METI estimates. According to the ministry's projections, exports of automobiles, machinery and electronics--this nation's three major industries--will decline. Real GDP for 2020 will be pushed down by 10.5 trillion yen, and 812,000 jobs will be lost. An investment promotion program to be compiled by the government's inward investment roundtable might stipulate early participation in the TPP and promotion of EPAs, as well as corporate tax cuts. According to Nippon Keidanren estimates, such a program could see total domestic capital investment rise to about 104.4 trillion yen in 2020, about 60 percent up from last year's 62.7 trillion yen. Many manufacturers are now accelerating plans to transfer production bases to other countries, in response to the considerable decline in their competitiveness caused by the yen's appreciation. It is no exaggeration to say the state of the domestic manufacturing sector 10 years from now will be decided entirely by how Japan proceeds on the TPP. The government has little time left to make a decision.


