<span class="underline">As the Obama administration pursues nuclear weapons reductions, analysts are revisiting proposals to modify, or even eliminate, parts of the U.S. strategic triad of land-based missiles, submarines, and bombers. Triad talk has trickled into both the specialty press and provincially-interested local newspapers. </span><span style="font-size: 8pt;"> Conventional wisdom holds that nuclear-capable submarines are the crème de la crème of deterrence. Because they are invulnerable to an enemy first strike, submarines offer a guaranteed retaliatory capability that leaders would not feel pressured to “use or lose” in a crisis situation. Reflecting conventional wisdom, a senior Pentagon official said last week that submarines "are and have been the centerpiece, the core, of our deterrent…It's likely that they'll remain that. Whatever we do with nuclear weapons, we ought to get that right." </span><span class="underline">Though few have questioned the overall merit of ballistic missile submarines, concern has been expressed before about the risks involved in placing such a large proportion of U.S. nuclear forces aboard relatively few delivery vehicles. </span><span style="font-size: 8pt;"> During the Cold War, it was feared that the Soviet Union might produce a technological breakthrough that would allow it to detect American submarines. The Heritage Foundation warned that the Soviets were working on non-acoustic space-based detection that would allow them to “scan large swaths of ocean space.” Such warnings often were issued, not surprisingly, in support of investing in new ICBMs or bombers as an alternative to submarines. Though this and lesser detection technologies didn’t pan out, the implications were clear even to arms controllers. As Herbert Scoville Jr. wrote in 1982, “The fewer submarines kept at sea, the easier it will be for the Russians to wipe them out in a surprise attack.” Concern has petered out since the end of the Cold War, but it hasn’